  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>SaaS Transition:</strong> MSI continues to shift its business model to recurring software revenue (Cloud-based command center software). Accelerating this transition could expand margins faster than 11% FCF growth implies.</li>
    <li><strong>International Expansion:</strong> They dominate North America but have a smaller footprint in Europe and Asia. Winning massive national safety networks abroad offers huge untapped upside.</li>
    <li><strong>Video Security & AI:</strong> The acquisition of Avigilon and Pelco positioned them well. Rapid adoption of AI-enabled analytics in enterprise video security could drive massive unexpected growth.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>UK Airwave Dispute:</strong> The UK CMA (Competition and Markets Authority) ordered MSI to cut prices on the Airwave network, threatening hundreds of millions in high-margin revenue. Further adverse rulings pose a tangible risk.</li>
    <li><strong>High Debt Load:</strong> MSI operates with significant debt ($9.6B total debt). A sustained high-interest-rate environment increases refinancing costs, pressuring net income and FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>Municipal Budget Cuts:</strong> Although public safety is usually the last thing cut, severe state and local government budget shortfalls could delay massive infrastructure upgrades.</li>
  </ul>

